AB  - The studies included within this dissertation work addressed how the human brain adaptively combines information from different senses in order to make the best use of what may be a less-than-ideal scenario within any one sense. In the first series of studies, subjects used a laser pointer within a dark room to locate lights, sounds, or light-sound combinations presented around them; they did so both in conditions of normal vision, and while wearing vision-blurring glasses. Additionally, subjects were tested on the effects of blurred vision using functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI). Intriguingly, we found that not only did subjects show different strategies in dealing with impaired vision, but also that this was related to different patterns of activity within sensory cortex of the brain. In conjunction with this, poorer performance from having blurred vision was readily overcome by use of the combined visual-auditory signal. An additional study investigated the impact of specialized long-term training on this type of interactions, in which we tested trained music conductors within a similar task. We found that, interestingly, their ability to locate sounds in space was greatly improved relative to non-musicians, and they also showed an "enhancement" with combined visual-auditory stimuli that is not observed in the general population. A separate series of studies examined how the brain combines information from different senses when it occurs very close together in time, and how this process might be altered in dyslexic individuals. In these studies, subjects performed a visual discrimination task that also involved sounds occurring at a slightly different time. We found that not only did the inclusion of these sounds alter subjects' perceptual acuity, but also that this effect normally occurs only under very specific conditions of visual-auditory synchrony (i.e., when almost simultaneous). However, dyslexic subjects, who have been shown previously to have auditory discrimination difficulties, display a very different trend---the "multisensory" effect is observed under almost all conditions tested. Through the use of fMRI, we were able to describe the physiological basis of this effect, and propose how an altered neural architecture in dyslexia might relate to the reading disorders commonly associated with these individuals. (Abstract shortened by UMI.) (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
