AB  - The teaching and learning of music has been the focus of much research in the areas of education, psychology, music education and music psychology. Finding new ways to improve student learning has been taken on as a serious challenge and new designs and technologies have been created by all of these disciplines. Most educational researchers and practitioners would agree that teachers who have multiple means of addressing differences in student learning styles are holding the keys to their pupils' success. Recent educational research has uncovered the value of learning through the use of semiotics and other means that address multiple ways of knowing. Mental Imagery (MI) has proven to be successful as an educational technique by incorporating whatever means possible to enable students to create mental pictures that they may retain. This work includes the use of multisensory learning, is experiential in nature, addresses student emotional growth and aesthetic experience and can be made more effective with cooperative learning technology and student input. Although imagery has been employed in music therapy settings as an elicited response to programmed music, no formal studies have been conducted using MI as an intervening design to improve effectiveness in music education. The purpose of this study has been to look at the use of mental imagery in an elementary school music classroom. Of key focus are the students and the types of images that help them to learn, the facilitative work of the teacher and the relationships between students and teacher. Initial work done in a pilot study showed promise for connecting cognitive and affective learning while improving student accomplishment and interest. In an ongoing, naturalistic study, the use of MI as created by teachers and students to facilitate student learning of music has been recorded, documented and analyzed as educational events have unfolded. Through the use of interviews, document review, on-site observat