AB  - The multistage process of auditory skills include detection to sound, discrimination between sounds, and identification. Helping hearing-impaired children function successfully from sensory/primitive throughout linguistic stages is important for the development of speech perception and production. The Multisensory Sound Lab is educational technology developed for use by groups of children who are deaf or hearing impaired. It provides simultaneous visual, tactile, and auditory information in response to acoustic inputs. The amount and type of multisensory reinforcements can be adjusted by the user. Example applications of the Sound Lab include sound detection, sound comprehension (where the children were instructed to name orally and manually soft and loud sounds), gross vocalization, articulation, and music enrichment. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2023 APA, all rights reserved)
